owl:AnnotationProperty.rdfs:comment: A derivation is a transformation of an entity into another, an update of an entity resulting in a new one, or the construction of a new entity based on a pre-existing entity.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'based on' property relates an Algorithm to some other Algorithm that provides a basic technique for the first Algorithm. This relation can help to derive the relevant pubications/ blog posts to the other algorithms that needed to understand this algorithm.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: based on

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'belongs to' property relates an 'Problem' to a 'Complexity Class'. This relation can be helpful for researchers to explore the possibilities of quantum computing.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: belongs to

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'over' property depicts over which 'Classical Algorithm' a 'Quantum Algorithm' or 'Hybrid Quantum-Classical Algorithm' achieves indicated expected speedup.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: over

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Answers the question:What is the implementation of this algorithm?
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has implementation

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: A relation between an machine learning algogorithm and description of its hyperparameter in a textual form.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has hyperparameter

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Ansers the following question: Which algorithm is implemented by the particular implementation?
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: implements

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: This property depicts over which 'Classical Algorithm' a 'Quantum Algorithm' or a 'Hybrid Quantum-Classical Algorithm' achieves indicated expected speedup.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: achieves quantum speedup over

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: This property relates two algorithms that solve the same problem, but the domain algorithm solves the problem more effitiently than the range algorithm.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: achieves speedup over

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: This relation between two algorithms exist when an algorithm add improvements to another existing algorithm.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: improves

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'realizes' property relates an 'Computational Resource' to a 'Computational Model'. This relation can be used in the future to derive devices, on which an Implementation is executable.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: realizes

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'realized in' property relates an 'Computational Model' to a 'Computational Resource'. This relation can be used in the future to derive devices, on which an Implementation is executable.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: realized in

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: The 'depends on' property relates an 'Implementation' to a 'Software Tool'. This relation can be used to derive implementations that uses an specific framework, i. e. qiskit, TensorflowQuantum etc.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: depends on

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Quantum technologies used to create a quantum hardware.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: quantum technology

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Comes as String (in LatTex form or as simple textual description)
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: pseudocode

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Link to the implementation/software/algorithm explanation that is not a publication, e. g. a blogpost.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: article link

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: A short description of the algorithm (Purpose, Idea)
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: intent

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: The advantage in runtime obtained by a quantum algorithm over the classical methods for the same task.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: expected quantum speedup

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Specifies the date "YYYY-MM-DD" when the publication was printed.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: date

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Specifies the title of the publication.
owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:label: title

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that is based only on the subclasses of the 'Classical Computational Model'.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Classical Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that solves an AI problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Artifical Intelligence Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that is based on some Subclass of the 'Quantum Computation Model' AND some subclass of the 'Classical Computational Model'
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Hybrid Quantum-Classical Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that solves a machine learning problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Machine Learning Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that is based only on the subclasses of the 'Quantum Computation Model' .
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Quantum Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that solves a mathematical problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Mathematical Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that solves a search problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Search Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Algorithm that solves a sorting problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sorting Algorithm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects runs of a source code on a hardware with a specific algorithm configuration.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Execution

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A real industial use case/problem in its context including application data, implementation and a clearly defined goal.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Application

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Data is a data item composed of data examples and it may be of a various level of granularity and complexity. With regard to granularity, it can be a whole dataset (for instance, one main table and possibly other tables), or only a single table, or only a feature (e.g., a column of a table), or only an instance (e.g., row of a table), or a single feature-value pair. With regard to complexity, data examples are characterized by their datatype, which may be arbitrarily complex (e.g., instead of a table it can be an arbitrary graph).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Data

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects datasets that can be used for algorithms execution. Example of individuals of the datasets class can include: Iris dataset, FaceScrub dataset, IMDB-WIKI dataset, and others.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Dataset
owl:Class.skos:editorialNote: Examples in rdfs:comment are cited from the Paper "ML-Schema: An interchangeable format for description of machine learning experiments".

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This concept specifies a feauture contained in a dataset. Examples of individuals of features that appear in the Iris dataset are as follows: sepal length, sepal width, petal length, petal width, and class.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Feature
owl:Class.skos:editorialNote: Examples in rdfs:comment are cited from the Paper "ML-Schema: An interchangeable format for description of machine learning experiments".

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Describes an evaluation of an algorithm using specific metrics.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Evaluation

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects vendors that provide access to quantum computational resources.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Quantum Provider

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects different software resources.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Software

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects various frameworks, libraries, SDKs, or APIs that developers can use for implementing an algorithm.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Software Tool

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Contains languages that have a human readable syntax.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Programming Language

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects a low-level machine languages used to instruct the computer which physical operation to perform on which bit.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Instruction Language

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects quantum programming languages or libraries names that define own syntax that is embedded in a classical programming language.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Quantum Programming Language

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A source code that can be executed.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Implementation

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects computational resources that realize only classical computational model.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Classical Computational Resource

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects computational resources that realize only quantum computational model.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Quantum Computational Resource

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects computational devices utilized for the execution of a programming code.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Computational Resource

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects methods for limiting errors that occur during information processing (possible phases for qc: state preparation, unitary transformation, measurement).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Error Correction

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Collects instances of publications about an algorithm, an algorithm implementation or an algorithm evaluation.
Publication/s about an algorithm.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Publication

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Provide the relevant information about an publication.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Publication Characterisitc

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A task to be done.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Problem Type

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Provide the relevant information about an implementation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Implementation Characterisitc

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Provide the relevant characterisitcs for an algorithm.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Algorithm Characterisitc

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: DataCharacteristic is a distinguishing quality or property that distinguish one data from another. Such characteristics are often statistical ones (e.g., the number of instances or the number of features of a data set). They may be also informationtheoretic measures (e.g., class entropy of a categorical data set) or geometric measures of data complexity (e.g., the highest discriminatory power of any single feature in the data set).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Data Characteristic

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Information about an algorithm, typically pseudocode or/and circuit, that describes a solution for the problem.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Solution

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Provides name of the publication author.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Publication Author

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Instance examples of 'Data Characteristic' are numberOfFeatures, numberOfInstances, numberOfMissingValues.
